•Okagbare runs Season’s Best in Olympics prep South African sprinter Akani Simbine broke Olusoji Fasuba’s 15-year African record in the men’s 100m when he ran a time of 9.84secs to win at the World Athletics Continental Tour in Hungary on Tuesday. Simbine placed first ahead of USA’s Michael Rodgers and Marvin Bracy in second and third positions respectively to take one hundredth off Fasuba’s previous record of 9.85secs set in 2006 in Doha, Qatar. Nigeria’s Blessing Okagbare also ran a Season’s Best 10.89secs to place fourth in a star-studded women’s 100m final. Jamaica’s Elaine Thompson-Herah won the race in 10.71secs, ahead of compatriot Shelly-Ann Fraser-Pryce and Ivorian Marie-Josee Ta Lou, who placed second and third respectively with 10.82secs and 10.86secs. The competition held with less than 20 days before the commencement of the 2020 Olympics in Tokyo, Japan. The PUNCH had earlier reported that wind stopped Okagbare from becoming the joint-fastest woman alive when she ran a time of 9.63m at the Athletics Federation of Nigeria National Trials held at the Yaba College of Technology, Lagos last month. The race was not legal after a non-legal wind of 2.7m/s was recorded. Divine Oduduru and Chukwuebuka Enekwechi were the other Nigerians at the WA Continental Tour. Oduduru ran a time of 20.38secs to place third behind Simbine and Alonso Edward in race two of the men’s 200m, while Enekwechi placed fourth in the men’s shot put with a throw of 21.43m. Copyright PUNCH. All rights reserved. This material, and other digital content on this website, may not be reproduced, published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed in whole or in part without prior express written permission from PUNCH. Contact: theeditor@punchng.com